ðŸ“Œ Does the Output Match Benford's Law?
âž¤ Probably Not, and Here's Why:

    Small Sample Size (n=10):

        Benfordâ€™s Law works best with large, naturally distributed datasets.

        With only 10 values per column, the distribution of leading digits is erratic.

    Randomly Generated Data:

        sales_value is normally distributed, not scale-invariant â€” violating assumptions of Benfordâ€™s Law.

        Other features (num_clients, etc.) are from uniform or limited ranges, which donâ€™t follow Benfordâ€™s Law.

    Expected Outcome:

        High MAD values

        Low p-values (if counts match) â†’ indicating deviation from Benford

        Plots will show poor fit to Benfordâ€™s curve

